Initial Evictions Analysis

Roxanne Ready, Maya Pottiger, Ryan Little, Sean McGoey, Sean Mussenden

7/8/2020

Data Analysis for Eviction Data

This markdown file provides analysis of eviction filing data for 21 localities in 2020. The Howard Center gathered data for 11 cities. The other 10 come from data gathered by Eviction Lab. The cities are:

  • Milwaukee, Wisconsin (HC)
  • Cleveland (EL), Cincinnati (EL) and Toledo (HC), Ohio
  • Shelby (Memphis) (HC), Tennessee
  • New Orleans (HC), Louisiana
  • Tulsa (HC) and Oklahoma City (HC), Oklahoma
  • Houston (EL) and Austin (EL), Texas
  • Kansas City (EL), Missouri
  • Pinellas (St. Petersburg) (HC), Hillsborough (Tampa) (HC) and Jacksonville (EL), Florida
  • Fulton (HC) and Dekalb (HC) (Atlanta) and Chatham (Savannah) (HC), Georgia
  • Richmond (EL), Virginia
  • St. Louis (EL), Missouri
  • Pittsburgh (EL), Pennsylvania
  • Boston (EL), Mass.

The top line findings:

  • Since a federal moratorium on certain eviction filings took effect with the signing of the CARES Act at the end of March, evictions filings have continued in more than 20 cities using data gathered by the Howard Center and Eviction Lab. Between March 27 and the end of June, more than 20,000 evictions were filed in these 21 areas.
  • In all but one city we examined (Milwaukee, Wisconsin), eviction filings in June remained far below historical eviction filing rates, following the implementation of local, state and federal policies designed to forestall eviction filings.
  • Eviction filings were generally at normal levels in January and February, but were well below historic norms in March. They hit their their lowest point relative to historic norms in April and May, with a less dramatic dropoff in June. But some cities are closer than others to hitting normal levels again. The following cities had higher relative rates of eviction filings than other cities in our data: Milwaukee, Wisconsin (+15% from June in prior years); Cleveland, Ohio (-30% from June in prior years); Shelby (Memphis), Tennessee (-53% from June 2019); Oklahoma City, Oklahoma (-54% from June in prior years).
  • We are able to reliably examine the outcome of eviction cases in three cities: Hillsborough (Tampa), Florida; Oklahoma City, Oklahoma; and Shelby (Memphis), Tennessee. Since the CARES Act moratorium took effect at the end of March, the data shows the courts there are issuing orders (writs of evictions) at a lower rate relative to historical norms and that those orders are being used to actually evict people (writs of evictions served) at lower rates relative to historical norms. It’s unclear why this is happening.
  • In each city we were able to examine plaintiffs, a small number of landlords are responsible for a large number of evictions. Further cleaning is being done, more intital data is below.
  • Still in process: demographic analysis of geocoded rental properties subject to eviction.
  • Still in process: matching landlords against properties not supposed to be evicting people because of CARES Act.
  • Still in process: matching landlords across cities.
  • Still to come: matching landlords against recipients of Paycheck Proteciton Act.

Filings Analysis

Using data from Eviction Lab and our own scraped data, the Howard Center examined eviction filings in 21 cities. Since the CARES Act took effect on March 27, and a host of state and local moratoria designed to forestall evictions, more than 20,000 eviction cases have been filed.

This chart shows one way of visualizing the reduction in eviction filings relative to historic norms. It shows the percentage change in filings in each month of 2020 relative to the number of filings in January 2020, before eviction moratoria took effect.

In June 2020, eviction filings were still down by more than 90 percent in Austin, Richmond, St. Louis, Jacksonville, Pittsburgh and Boston; down by more than 80 percent in Dekalb and Fulton counties; down by more than 70 percent in Cincinnati, Toledo, Chatham (GA), Hillsborough and Kansas City.

This chart also shows another trend we identified: though still low by historic standards, evictions have started to creep back up in some cities. For example, eviction filings were down by 96 percent in Tulsa in April, but were only 62 percent lower in June. In Cleveland, eviction filings were down by 99 percent in April, but only 24 percent lower in June. And after major reductions in April and May, evictions in Milwaukee were higher in June than in January

Writ Analysis

Eviction filings are only one step of the process. In most cities, for someone to actually be legally evicted, the court must order the eviction (with a writ) and the writ must be served.

We only have relible writ data for Hillsborough (Tampa), Oklahoma City and Shelby (Memphis). This chart shows the number of writs issued by the court in each of those cities by month dating back to January 2019.

It shows that writs were still being issued after March 2020, but at a lower rate than historic norms.
